{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598342"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:36:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:36:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15463"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15463"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.25,0.05,0.05,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8154"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75963"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8154","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8154"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15463"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61464"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"2067"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"9582"},{"type":"tags","id":"9583"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19756"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19759"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75963"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA one-year-old presents to the emergency department with harsh stridor and a barking cough that developed gradually over three days. The child appears unwell, has difficulty swallowing, and has not improved with nebulised adrenaline or oral dexamethasone.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Viral croup","Acute epiglottitis","Bacterial tracheitis","Retropharyngeal abscess","Adenoidal hypertrophy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical features are characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Ebacterial tracheitis\u003C/strong\u003E, which presents with gradual onset of croup-like symptoms that respond poorly to standard treatments. The condition represents a bacterial infection of the tracheal mucosa, typically caused by \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E or \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other conditions can be distinguished:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral croup\u003C/strong\u003E typically has acute onset and responds well to corticosteroids and nebulised adrenaline\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute epiglottitis\u003C/strong\u003E has rapid onset (hours) with high fever, drooling, and characteristic tripod position\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetropharyngeal abscess\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with neck stiffness and severe pain on swallowing but less prominent respiratory symptoms\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdenoidal hypertrophy\u003C/strong\u003E causes chronic nasal obstruction and snoring rather than acute stridor\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBacterial tracheitis is sometimes called \u0027membranous croup\u0027 due to the presence of thick mucopurulent secretions in the trachea. It represents an intermediate severity between viral croup and epiglottitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Bacterial tracheitis presents with croup-like symptoms but has gradual onset over days and poor response to standard croup treatments","Bacterial tracheitis is typically caused by Staphylococcus aureus or Streptococcus pneumoniae infection of the tracheal mucosa","Key features distinguishing bacterial tracheitis from viral croup include toxic appearance, harsh stridor, and dysphagia"],"references":["Mason, R. J., Broaddus, V. C., Martin, T. R., King, T. E., Schraufnagel, D., Murray, J. F., \u0026 Nadel, J. A. (2010). Murray and Nadel\u0027s textbook of respiratory medicine E-book: 2-volume set. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Burton LV, Lofgren DH, Silberman M. Bacterial Tracheitis. [Updated 2023 Jun 30]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470240/","Smith DK, McDermott AJ, Sullivan JF. Croup: Diagnosis and Management. Am Fam Physician. 2018 May 1;97(9):575-580. PMID: 29763253."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61464"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15463"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61464"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T18:33:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T18:34:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8154"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75963"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","na